# React Re-rendering with Object Props

This is a classic React issue caused by **reference equality** — objects are compared by reference, not by value.

## The Problem

```jsx
// ❌ Parent Component - Creates NEW object every render
function Parent() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  return (
    <Child 
      data={{ name: 'John', age: 30 }}  // New object every render!
    />
  );
}

// ❌ Child Component
function Child({ data }) {
  console.log('Child rendered!');  // Runs every time Parent renders
  return <div>{data.name}</div>;
}
```

Even though `data` looks identical, React sees **two different objects** (`{} !== {}`).

---

## Solutions

### 1. Move the object **outside** the component (for static data)

```jsx
// ✅ Object created once, same reference always
const staticData = { name: 'John', age: 30 };

function Parent() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
  return <Child data={staticData} />;
}
```

### 2. Use `useMemo` for dynamic object creation

```jsx
function Parent({ userId }) {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  // ✅ Only recreates when userId changes
  const data = useMemo(() => ({
    userId,
    timestamp: Date.now()
  }), [userId]);

  return <Child data={data} />;
}
```

### 3. Use `React.memo` with custom comparison

```jsx
// ✅ Only re-renders when props actually change
const Child = React.memo(({ data }) => {
  console.log('Child rendered!');
  return <div>{data.name}</div>;
}, (prevProps, nextProps) => {
  // Custom comparison function
  return prevProps.data.id === nextProps.data.id;
});
```

### 4. Same issue with **functions** passed as props

```jsx
// ❌ New function every render
<Child onClick={() => handleClick(id)} />

// ✅ useCallback preserves reference
<Child onClick={useCallback(() => handleClick(id), [id])} />
```

---

## Quick Reference

| Cause | Solution |
|-------|----------|
| Inline object in JSX | Move outside or use `useMemo` |
| Inline function in JSX | Use `useCallback` |
| Parent re-renders | Wrap child in `React.memo` |
| Unnecessary state | Check if state is actually needed |

---

## Debugging Tip

```jsx
// Add this to identify what's causing re-renders
useEffect(() => {
  console.log('Props changed:', { data });
}, [data]);
```

