New object reference created each render. Parent re-renders → inline object `{value: x}` = new ref → child sees "changed" → re-render.

React uses reference equality (`===`), not deep equality. Contents identical, but memory address different.

## Solutions

**1. Memoize the object (most common)**
```jsx
// Parent
const options = useMemo(() => ({ theme: 'dark', size: 'lg' }), []);

return <Child config={options} />;
```

**2. Memoize the child**
```jsx
export const Child = memo(({ config }) => {
  // only re-renders when config reference changes
});
```

**3. Lift state or flatten props**
```jsx
// Instead of passing object
return <Child theme="dark" size="lg" />;
```

## Why this happens

```jsx
// BAD - new object every render
<Child config={{ theme: 'dark' }} />

// Parent component re-renders = new {}={} literal = new reference = re-render child
```

## Rule of thumb

Pass primitives when possible. Objects/arrays/functions = memoize or memo-wrap them.

