Here is a complete implementation of a React Error Boundary.

To comply with React's architecture, **Error Boundaries must be Class Components**. Functional components (using Hooks) cannot implement an Error Boundary because the error handling lifecycle methods (`componentDidCatch`) do not exist within the Hooks API.

### 1. The ErrorBoundary Component (`ErrorBoundary.jsx`)

This component manages the error state and provides the UI with a retry mechanism.

```jsx
import React, { Component } from 'react';

class ErrorBoundary extends Component {
  constructor(props) {
    super(props);
    this.state = { 
      hasError: false, 
      error: null, 
      errorInfo: null 
    };
  }

  // This lifecycle method is invoked after an error has occurred in a descendant component.
  // It updates the state so the next render shows the fallback UI.
  static getDerivedStateFromError(error) {
    return { hasError: true, error };
  }

  // This lifecycle method is invoked when an error is thrown in a descendant component.
  // Use it to log error details to an external service (e.g., Sentry, Datadog).
  componentDidCatch(error, errorInfo) {
    // Log the error to an error reporting service
    console.error("ErrorBoundary caught an error: ", error, errorInfo.componentStack);

    // You could also update state here if you want to track errorInfo details
    // (though getDerivedStateFromError is better for state updates that affect render)
    this.setState({ errorInfo });
  }

  // Handler to reset the error state, allowing the user to retry
  handleReset = () => {
    this.setState({ hasError: false, error: null, errorInfo: null });
    // Optionally, you can trigger a re-render of the specific component
    // by updating a key prop passed to the children, 
    // but resetting state here is usually sufficient for the UI.
  };

  render() {
    if (this.state.hasError) {
      // Default Fallback UI
      return (
        <div style={styles.container}>
          <div style={styles.card}>
            <h2 style={styles.title}>Oops!</h2>
            <p style={styles.message}>Something went wrong while rendering this component.</p>

